The paper deals with developing a distributed Kalman filtering algorithm over wireless sensor networks, which involves topics related to control systems (cs.SY), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), information theory (cs.IT), mathematical analysis (cs.MA), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper discusses the challenges of poor local sensor estimation and network topology changes, which are common issues in wireless sensor networks. The proposed algorithm is based on randomized consensus strategy, which involves stochastic selection of neighbors and probabilistic convergence analysis. The paper also proposes an optimization problem to minimize the average expected state estimation error, which involves convex optimization techniques. Overall, the paper covers a wide range of topics related to computer science and engineering, but the most relevant sub-categories are likely to be cs.SY and cs.NI.
